IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: Detailed Crash Investigation Report (For review by the MSPCrash Team) Section I. - Introduction: On March 16, 2023, at approximately 0956 hours, Troopers from the McHenry Barrack and EMS responded to Maryland route 495 south of Dung HillRoad in Garrett County for a two vehicle collision. The following vehicles and occupants were involved in the crash: Vehicle 1 (V1): 2001 Ford Taurus Driver 1 (D1): Brandy Jo McKenzie Vehicle 2 (V2): 2019 Ram 1500 Driver 2 (D2): Ryan Richard Evans V1 became engulfed in fire as a result of the collision, McKenzie was removed from the vehicle prior to the fire and was pronounced dead on scene by EMS. Evans did not require treatment for injuries. It was determined that V1 had been traveling northbound on MD 495, when it failed to negotiate a sharp right hand turn south of Dung HillRoad. V1 crossed into the southbound lane and into the path of V2, causing the right front of V1 to strike the front of V2. Section II. - Scene Description: (The following descriptions are based on the area where the collision occurred.) Primary Roadway: Maryland Route 495 MD 495 was a two lane roadway constructed of asphalt, which ran primarily north and south. A small paved shoulder was to the outside of each travel lane. The lanes were separated by a double yellow line, rumble strips and in pavement reflectors. Each lane was separated from their respective shoulders by a white fog line. The northbound lane traveled down a hill, around a right-hand curve and then into the uphill straightaway where the crash occurred. The southbound lane was traveling down a straight hill. The posted speed limit was 50 mph. A right curve ahead sign was posted for northbound traffic on the down hill south of the curve. The below photo shows the scene looking north. base64," style="height:437px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> The below Google Earth photo shows the overview of the scene with north at the top of the photo. base64," style="height:474px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> Environmental Conditions: At the time of the crash it was approximately 44 degrees Fahrenheit and mostly cloudy. There was no precipitation and the roadway was dry. Section III. - Scene Evidence: No evidence was located in the travel lane. Both vehicles were at uncontrolled final rest at the entrance to the driveway to 13041 Bittinger Road, both facing away from the road. V1 was further south and further off of the road with the front left corner against a wooden fence post which had been pushed loose. The rear of V2 was over the southbound shoulder. Debris from both vehicles was spread across the driveway. The scene was digitally photographed. Ground control points (GCP) were placed throughout the scene and documented with an Emlid RS+ GNSS. The GCPs would be used to scale an orthomosaic image created from photographs taken by a sUAS. The scene was then mapped with the sUAS: MSP Syscom case number: 23-00858 NOTAM: AOO 03/153 Aircraft:Crash Team UAS 9 FA34WNR733 Autel Evo II 6K HA9921441404 Flight Time: 12 minutes 261 digital photographs were taken Mapping was completed with a manual flight Diagram Completion: Pix4D Processing 254 of the 261 sUAS digital photographs were processed in the Pix4D desktop application. Pix4D takes those photographs and looks for common points in each of the photos. Those points are then used to generate a point cloud and then an orthomosaic image. A review of the Pix4D quality report showed that all of the 254 images were calibrated and geolocated. All 10 of the GNSS GCPs were put into Pix4d. All of the GCPs were used by Pix4D to scale the image created by Pix4D. The mean error for the GCPs was .022 feet or .264 inches. There was excellent overlap of the mapping area that contained the physical evidence. Overall, the image produced by Pix4D was an accurate representation of the scene when the sUAS was flown. Map360 Processing The Pix4D generated orthomosaic tiff file was used to create a diagram in the Leica Map360 software. The evidence was labeled, and a final diagram was created. Section IV. - Vehicle(s) Involved: Vehicle #1:2001 Ford Taurus, MD 541Z36 V1 was a blue 2001 Ford Taurus bearing Maryland registration 541Z36. The entire passenger compartment and part of the engine compartment sustained fire damage. The main impact occurred to the right side of the front bumper and the front of the right side of the vehicle. The right front wheel was pushed back, and the right front door was crushed back. There was minor damage to the left front corner from striking the fence post. This vehicle was supported by the Bosch Crash Data Retrieval (CDR) system to have its Airbag Control Module (ACM) imaged. The vehicle was towed from the scene by JTC Towing to their tow lot. The below photo shows the right front corner of V1. base64," style="height:471px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> Vehicle #2:2019 Ram 1500, MD 3CC6997 V2 was a white 2019 Ram 1500 with a cap on the cargo bed. The damage was contained to the front of the vehicle. The front bumper was pushed down and back. The bottom of the radiator was pushed into the engine. The rear of the right fender was pushed into the right front door. The top of the hood caught fire from the fire of V1. The left front window had cracked and the left rear window completely shattered. Both frontal airbags had deployed and the drivers seat belt was tight against the B pillar. V2 was towed from the scene by Grantsville Truck and Trailer. This vehicle was supported by the CDR system to have its ACM imaged.Ryan Evans provided written consent to image the ACM. The below photo shows the right front corner of V2. base64," style="height:466px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> Section V. - Person(s) Involved: Person #1:Brandy Jo McKenzie, driver V1 Brandy McKenzie was the driver of V1. McKenzie was pronounced dead on scene and transported to the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner by Newman Funeral Home. An autopsy was performed on March 17, 2023 by Dr. Eli Goodman. The cause of death was blunt force trauma of the torso and the manner of death was, accident. The injuries were described as, devastating lethal blunt injuries of the torso, including multiple bilateral rib fractures in multiple planes, complete transection of the thoracic spinal column and spinal cord, injuries of the heart, lungs and aorta and massive internal hemorrhage. Toxicology tests were negative for illicit drugs and ethanol. Person #2:Ryan Richard Evans, driver V2 Ryan Evan was the driver of V2. Evans refused medical treatment on scene. He stated that he was driving south on MD 495 when he observed V1 traveling northbound and crossing the center line after exiting the curve. He believed the driver of V1 was trying to steer back into the northbound lane when they lost control. He stated he swerved V2 to the right to avoid V1, but they collided. He advised V1 was traveling at a high rate of speed. Section VI. - Follow-up Investigation: Date:March 16, 2023 I responded to the Grantsville Truck and Trailer lot to image the ACM of V2. The factory installed cable was removed from the ACM and CDR adapter F00K108387 and cable number F00K108785 were installed. The ACM was imaged using CDR software version 23.0.2. Copies of the data were saved. Date:March 21, 2023 I responded to the JTC Towing lot to attempt to locate and image the ACM of V1. Due to the fire, numerous vehicle parts had melted on top of the ACM. After removing those parts, the factory installed cable was removed from the ACM and CDR cable number 02003043 was installed. The ACM was imaged using CDR software version 23.0.2. Copies of the data were saved. Date:April 10, 2023 I received the autopsy report for McKenzie which was described above. Section VII. - Analysis of Electronic Control Modules: V1: A non-deployment event was recovered from the ACM. The data limitations stated that speed, throttle position, brake application and other data were not recorded by the ACM of V1. The limitations also stated that a loss of power to the electrical system could result in no deceleration data being recorded. The data showed that no diagnostic codes were present when the data was recorded. The drivers seat belt was buckled for this event. No safety equipment deployed during this event. No data was available to positively link this data to this crash. The deceleration data showed No Data, probably due to damage to the electrical system. V2: A deployment event, (Most Recent Event) was recovered from the ACM. A review of the data limitations did not reveal anything that would invalidate the data. The ignition cycle when the ACM was imaged was 7,748 and 7,747 when the event was recorded, linking this data to the crash. The data showed that the drivers seat belt was unbuckled. The maximum change was -29.2 mph in velocity in the lateral direction at 196 ms and 9.3 mph in the lateral direction at 104 ms. No diagnostic trouble codes were present at the start of the event. Five seconds of pre-crash data was recorded in 1/10th of a second intervals. The data included vehicle speed, accelerator pedal and brake application in addition to other categories. At the start of the recording V2 was traveling 64.6 mph with accelerator pedal application. The vehicle speed remained 64.6 until -3.6 seconds. At -3.5 seconds the vehicle began to slow and the brakes were applied and remained applied through the end of the recording. The vehicle continued to slow until time -.1 seconds when it was traveling 31.1 mph. The ABS system activated from -.9 seconds through the end of the recording. The below chart shows the full five seconds of data. base64," style="height:744px; margin:5px 10px; width:700px" /> Steering input was also recorded in 1/10th of second intervals. The steering wheel was held relatively straight until -1.1 seconds with a right-hand input began and then increased and remained through the end of the recording. Section VIII. - Speed Analysis: V2 had slowed to near 31 mph at the time of the crash. Section IX. - Crash Dynamics: V1 was traveling northbound when it crossed into the southbound lane. V2 began to slow and attempted to swerve to the right, but both vehicles collided in an off-set head-on crash. The impact caused V1 to rotate counterclockwise, travel off of the roadway, strike a fence post and catch fire. V2 rotated clockwise and came to rest on the driveway. Section X. - Attachments that were included in for this report: The following items were attached to this report: ACRS Diagram Pix4D Quality Report Consent Form Written Statement CDR report x2 Autopsy report 125 scenedigital photographs uploaded to Veripic 261 sUAS digital photographs uploaded to Veripic 30 follow up digital photographs uploaded to Veripic Conclusion: On March 16, 2023, at approximately 0956 hours, Brandy Jo McKenzie was operating a 2001 Ford Taurus northbound on MD 495 south of Dung HillRoad. After traveling down a hill and around a right hand curve, McKenzie failed to keep the Ford in the northbound lane and crossed the double yellow line into the southbound lane. The Ford continued north in the southbound lane where it struck a southbound 2019 Ram 1500 which was operated by Ryan Evans. The impact caused both vehicles to rotate onto the southbound shoulder, where V1 struck a fence post. V1 caught fire which spread into the passenger compartment after McKenzie had been removed. McKenzie was pronounced dead on scene. V2 had slowed to near 31 mph at impact and the force of the impact was enough to stop V2 and rotate it 90 degrees. Brandy Jo McKenzie is at-fault for this crash, for failing to drive right of center. While the speed of V1 is not known, based on the post impact travel of both vehicles, it is believed that V1 was traveling above the posted speed limit. This case is closed due to the death of at-fault party. Sgt. David Zanoni Crash Team - Cumberland Office 1125 National Highway Cumberland, MD 21502 301-729-6470
